<h3 ALIGN="center"><!--mstheme--><font color="#CC3333"><font color="#FF0000">Students, police clash in Hebron</font><!--mstheme--></font></h3>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Hebron (West Bank) - </b>Hundreds of school students on 22 February stoned
the PA Education Department in downtown Hebron in protest against the PA refusal to meet
the demands of striking teachers for higher salaries and better working conditions.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">PA police intervened to disperse demonstrators, using truncheons. </p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">According to eyewitnesses, PA police officers from the &#147;Rapid
Intervention Squad&#148; arrived at the site and promptly began pushing the student
protestors. </p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Following the use of force against them by police, the protestors
responded by throwing stones at the police and the Education Department.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">According to local sources, 15 students were injured by police, including
one student who got a fractured arm. Injured students were taken to the Ahli Hospital in
Hebron.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The disturbances were sparked by the continuing strike of thousands of
teachers who are demanding an increase in their salaries.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The teachers had staged a strike to force the PA to negotiate a settlement
which the teachers hope will improve, including a pay raise.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The PA thus far refused to sit down with the teachers&#146; leaders,
accusing them of &#147;breaking the law&#148; and of &#147;harbouring political goals
going beyond the issue of salaries.&#148;</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The PA said in a statement that it recognized the &#147;legitimacy of the
teachers&#146; grievances&#148;, adding that the &#147;strike was not the way to solve the
problem.&#148;</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The teachers&#146; strike has been conspicuous in the southern part of the
West Bank, particularly in Hebron and Bethlehem.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">However, reports from Nablus and Jenin recently spoke of thousands of
teachers joining the strike.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The average Palestinian teacher receives a monthly salary of up to $US
340, a sum the teachers contend does not meet the basic necessities for basic, decent
living.</p>

