<h3 ALIGN="center"><!--mstheme--><font color="#CC3333"><font color="#FF0000">Abdul Sattar Qassem arrested&#133;again</font></b><!--mstheme--></font></h3>
<b>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Occupied Jerusalem- PT</b></p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Around midnight on Friday, 18 February, Palestinian Authority police
arrested the noted Palestinian academic and political activist Abdul Sattar Qassem.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The Palestinian Human Rights Organization (LAW) quoted Qassem&#146;s wife
as saying that two agents of the PA police&#146;s Criminal Squad arrived at the
couple&#146;s home in Nablus and arrested the 50-year-old professor of Political Science
at the Najah National University.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Mrs. Qassem said the two officers, who did not produce an arrest warrant,
said they had an order to arrest her husband issued by PA President Yasser Arafat and his
Gaza Police Chief Ghazi al-Jabali.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">She said she did not know where they took him.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The PA-run electronic media made no mention of Qassem&#146;s arrest, and
even the semi-official printed media, which are normally less tightly controlled, reported
the arrest only on 21 February, three days after it had been circulated by international
news agencies and human rights organizations.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Qassem was among the 20 Palestinian intellectuals who, nearly three months
ago, circulated a strongly worded petition castigating Arafat&#146;s regime for its
political incompetence and for graft and corruption.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The petition then sparked widespread reactions among Palestinians within
the autonomous enclaves, as well as in the Diaspora, prompting Arafat to order the arrest
of the bulk of the petition&#146;s signatories.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">However, unlike other petitioners, who were incarcerated for nearly ten
days, Qassem and Ahmed Shaker Dudin (a veteran nationalist leader from Dura) were kept in
prison for 37 days for refusing to back down and recant the content of the petition. The
two were finally released on the day of Eidul Fitr, the feast marking the end of the holy
month of Ramadan.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">It is not clear what prompted Arafat to order the arrest of Qassem again.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Palestinian sources in Nablus intimated that the arrest might have been an
attempt by the PA to forestall the circulation of a new petition stressing that the
Palestinian leadership, specifically Arafat, had no right to give up or compromise the
Palestinian refugees&#146; right of return.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The sources also said the new petition would also warn Israel and the
United States that any arrangement reached with Arafat that did not satisfy Palestinian
legitimate demands, including first and foremost the right of return for the refugees,
would not be binding upon the Palestinian people even if accepted and endorsed by Arafat.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">If true, such a petition would raise serious questions about Arafat&#146;s
legal ability to negotiate a &#147;deal&#148; on the refugees, and would also give more
credibility to the growing calls for a referendum in Palestine and the Diaspora on any
final status agreement which Arafat might strike with the Israelis.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Indeed, neither Israel nor the United States would welcome the referendum
idea, since they both know well that it would have no chance of success, given the intense
insistence by the vast majority of Palestinians on the right of return.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Meanwhile, thousands of Palestinian schoolteachers continued to boycott
classes for the second consecutive week in protest against lower salaries and the PA
failure to put into effect the Civil Service Law, which was passed last year by the PA
Legislative Council, adopted for one month, but then revoked for lack of funds.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">A spokesman for the teachers in Hebron refuted PA accusations that the
strike was politically motivated, arguing that &#147;a hungry teacher can&#146;t teach
well.&#148;</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The spokesman, Abdul Jawwad Al-Attrash, pointed out that the average
Palestinian teacher was receiving a monthly salary of between 1,400 and 1,600 NIS (roughly
US $350-$390), while the average Israeli teacher, who lives under virtually the same
economic conditions, received six times as much.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">So far, the PA has refused to negotiate with the striking teachers, let
alone meet their ostensibly right demands.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">The lion&#146;s share of the PA budget goes to the security agencies,
which leaves meagre allocations for the civilian sectors, such as health and education.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Also, in a related development, PA police closed down a local television
station in Hebron for airing an interview with Al-Attrash, in which he reportedly accused
the PA of pushing the teachers to leave the schools and seek employment on Israeli
construction sites.</p>

<p ALIGN="LEFT">Hebron police chief Tareq Zeid accused the Nawras television station of
&#147;incitement&#148; and &#147;endangering national interests in this crucial and
delicate phase of our struggle.&#148; </p>

